{"parentUuid":"b1975856-4823-4e28-afff-1bf96c735484","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01CumrnsfMNNe2y3QJse9VR3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Ra3Zkrgf1UdUJbksuhvCEX","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"How git push --mirror handles refs","subagent_type":"Explore","prompt":"I'm trying to understand how `git push --mirror` works at the protocol/code level, specifically:\n\n1. **Does a git ref have any concept of \"fast-forward\" baked into it?** I.e., is FF a property of the ref itself, or is it purely an enforcement check at update time? Look at how refs are stored (refs.c, refs.h, refs/files-backend.c) and report what a ref *actually is* on disk and in memory.\n\n2. **Where is the fast-forward check actually enforced during a push?** I believe this lives in receive-pack (the server side), not the ref data structure. Find the check. Confirm whether non-FF updates are rejected at the protocol level or just by default policy.\n\n3. **What does `--mirror` actually do differently from a normal `git push`?** Find the flag handling in builtin/push.c or transport.c. Specifically:\n   - Does it set \"force\" on all updates?\n   - Does it bypass FF checks for non-branch refs (notes, pull refs, etc.)?\n   - Does it have special handling for `refs/notes/*` or other namespaces?\n\n4. **Are tags and notes treated differently from branches re: FF in standard git?** I know tag updates require `-f` by default — confirm where that check lives. Is there equivalent rejection logic for notes or arbitrary refs?\n\nThe repo is at `/Users/soph/Work/entire/research/git` — it's the upstream git source tree. Focus on the C sources, not the docs.\n\nReport file paths with line numbers and quote the key code blocks. Under 500 words. The goal is to ground a \"do refs have FF semantics at all\" answer in actual git internals."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1260,"cache_read_input_tokens":40365,"output_tokens":785,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1260,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":785,"cache_read_input_tokens":40365,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1260,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1260},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CbAG3XFFK6pXJZ39yQorX","type":"assistant","uuid":"8ea467af-0227-4696-8ec5-734d326f9bca","timestamp":"2026-05-18T15:20:25.959Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync","sessionId":"c6533991-5707-4094-a756-614132c9eb65","version":"2.1.143","gitBranch":"soph/changelog-0-5-0"}
{"parentUuid":"8ea467af-0227-4696-8ec5-734d326f9bca","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"eab0e9dd-6896-437f-9f47-a785bac60f4d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Ra3Zkrgf1UdUJbksuhvCEX","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect. Now I have all the pieces. Let me create a final summary:\n\n## Summary\n\nBased on my analysis of git's C source code, here are the answers to your questions:\n\n### 1. Do refs have \"fast-forward\" baked in?\n\n**No.** Refs are purely name→OID mappings (or symrefs). Looking at `refs.h` and `refs.c`, refs have no FF semantics intrinsic to their structure—they're just pointers. The transaction error codes in `refs.h` (lines 20-37) include no FF-related checks. A ref on disk in `refs/files-backend.c` is literally just a SHA1 or a symbolic reference. FF is entirely an enforcement policy applied at update time, not a property of the ref itself.\n\n### 2. Where is the fast-forward check enforced during push?\n\nThe FF check happens **client-side in `remote.c:set_ref_status_for_push()`** (lines 1653-1744), not in receive-pack.\n\nFor branches, `remote.c:1731` calls `ref_newer()` to test if the new OID is a descendant of the old one:\n```c\nelse if (!ref_newer(&ref->new_oid, &ref->old_oid))\n    reject_reason = REF_STATUS_REJECT_NONFASTFORWARD;\n```\n\nThe server-side **receive-pack.c:1582-1609** has a **second, independent FF check** controlled by `receive.denynonfastforwards` config, but it only applies to `refs/heads/*` (branches):\n```c\nif (deny_non_fast_forwards && !is_null_oid(new_oid) &&\n    !is_null_oid(old_oid) &&\n    starts_with(name, \"refs/heads/\")) {\n    // ... check if old_commit is ancestor of new_commit\n    if (!ret2) {\n        rp_error(\"denying non-fast-forward %s\", name);\n        ret = \"non-fast-forward\";\n    }\n}\n```\n\nNon-FF updates are rejected by default client-side policy, not the protocol.\n\n### 3. What does `--mirror` do differently?\n\n**`--mirror` sets both `TRANSPORT_PUSH_MIRROR` AND `TRANSPORT_PUSH_FORCE`** (`builtin/push.c:568`):\n```c\nOPT_BIT(0, \"mirror\", &flags, N_(\"mirror all refs\"),\n        (TRANSPORT_PUSH_MIRROR|TRANSPORT_PUSH_FORCE)),\n```\n\nThe force flag defeats FF rejections. Additionally, in `remote.c:1664-1665`, when `send_mirror=false` (normal push), refs without a local peer_ref are skipped. With `--mirror`, they're included:\n```c\nif (ref->peer_ref)\n    oidcpy(&ref->new_oid, &ref->peer_ref->new_oid);\nelse if (!send_mirror)\n    continue;  // Skip if no peer and not mirroring\n```\n\nThis allows pushing arbitrary refs (notes, pull refs, etc.). The force flag then exempts all of them from FF checks.\n\n### 4. Are tags and notes treated differently?\n\n**Tags require `-f` by default.** In `remote.c:1724-1725`, tags get rejected unconditionally if they already exist on the remote:\n```c\nif (starts_with(ref->name, \"refs/tags/\"))\n    reject_reason = REF_STATUS_REJECT_ALREADY_EXISTS;\n```\n\n**Notes and other arbitrary refs follow standard FF rules** (1731-1732). They're only rejected if they're non-FF updates to commits. Tags bypass FF logic entirely—they use an existence check instead."}]}]},"uuid":"8f9f3c75-e40c-49ce-a9ce-dc2ce5bd7b0b","timestamp":"2026-05-18T15:21:34.323Z","toolUseResult":{"status":"completed","prompt":"I'm trying to understand how `git push --mirror` works at the protocol/code level, specifically:\n\n1. **Does a git ref have any concept of \"fast-forward\" baked into it?** I.e., is FF a property of the ref itself, or is it purely an enforcement check at update time? Look at how refs are stored (refs.c, refs.h, refs/files-backend.c) and report what a ref *actually is* on disk and in memory.\n\n2. **Where is the fast-forward check actually enforced during a push?** I believe this lives in receive-pack (the server side), not the ref data structure. Find the check. Confirm whether non-FF updates are rejected at the protocol level or just by default policy.\n\n3. **What 